    <text>
        <body>
            <pb n="1"/>
            <p rend="align(right)">
                <placeName>Saint Paul</placeName>
                <date>December 8, 5623</date>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">
                <addressee>Revd. Isaac Leeser</addressee>
            </p>
            <p rend="indent(3)">Revd. Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Your worthy and kind letter<lb/> for which I am very greatly
                    <sic>oblige</sic> to you, was handed<lb/> to me by our worthy and most respected
                    <persName>Mr. Cardozo</persName>,<lb/> As the same does, and will do for you,
                whatever will be<lb/> in his might, and as his influence is very great, I am
                sure<lb/> your books will be sold here, of course he wrote to you.</p>
            <p rend="indent(1)">About my letter to <persName>Vice</persName>, certainly I leave
                every thing<lb/> to you, to act freely, according to your judgment. But believe<lb/>
                me sir; that my intention is not to give satisfaction, or to<lb/> justify myself
                before the world, since I know it <sic>to</sic> well that,<lb/> there are only, who
                wish to believe wrongly, and do not care<lb/> for the truth, with a very few
                exception. My only desire is, to<lb/> convince the so surnamed
                    <persName>Wise</persName> (yet a fool) that he cannot<lb/> injure me, and I am
                not afraid of him. The God whom I<lb/> serve, the holy One of
                    <placeName>Israel</placeName>, who <sic>deliverd</sic> me from the<lb/> mouths
                of lions and tigers, will protect and preserve me<lb/> from the violent, crazy, and
                mad dog-tar <persName>Vice</persName>, also.<lb/> And another thing, to let him know
                that I thank God<lb/> read every day, <add>קריאת שמע</add>, consequently I know the
                time<lb/> when I may read it, which it is according to some, <add>עד שיכיר בין זאב
                    לכלב</add><lb/>
                <add>על כל פשעים תכסה אהבה</add>, that there should be so much day light<lb/> that
                he may know the difference between a wolf and a dog.<lb/> Enough sir, I spoke
                    <sic>to</sic> much, and troubled you <sic>to</sic> much<lb/> about such an
                unworthy low mean fellow, I hope<lb/> you will for give me.</p>
            <pb n="2"/>
            <p rend="indent(1)">About my circumstances, as I know you to be an<lb/> unchangeable and
                immutable man, and you are<lb/> a friend indeed, <sic>And</sic>
                <add>כי אין צדיק בארץ אשר יעשה טוב ולא יחטא</add>, though I have my<lb/> failures
                more than enough, as there is none who fails not.<lb/>
                <add>Please sir send me a לוח if possible.</add>, Yet you always wish and desire
                my<lb/> welfare, I will let you know briefly, <sic>That</sic> during my<lb/> long
                and great sickness, I lost not only the little<lb/> money I made while at
                    <placeName>Nashville</placeName>, and <placeName>Memphis</placeName>, but<lb/>
                even my clothing and every thing I had, I came here<lb/> to tell <hi
                    rend="underline">you</hi>, naked and barefooted. But the all mercy-<lb/>ful
                heavenly father has sent his good angel before<lb/> me, that is the good kind and
                honourable <persName>Mr. Cardozo<add>?</add></persName><lb/> He not only takes care
                that I shall have every thing<lb/> needful for myself, but I am able to send to
                    <sic>send</sic> to<lb/> my family something every month. He also takes<lb/>
                care, and tries to make a man of me, which I have<lb/> not been till now, which
                brought me to all mis-<lb/>fortune I hope that I will prove to be a good
                disciple<lb/> and that he may be glad, that he led me, and trained me<lb/> up in the
                path I shall go. His lady though has servants<lb/> attends every thing in house, not
                trusting to a none Israelite<lb/> They are kind hearted and good and pious
                Israelites. I<lb/> hope, if not <sic>to</sic> much trouble, as I know your time<lb/>
                is very much occupied and engaged, to be honoured with<lb/> your answer. Till then I
                remain</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">Dear and Revd. Sir</p>
            <p rend="indent(5)">your most faithful and obedient servant</p>
            <p rend="indent(6)">
                <persName role="author">E. Marcuson</persName>
            </p>
            <p>Please sir send me a NS</p>
            <p>if possible.</p>
        </body>
